# ressources

Papers behind the {{ project_slug }} experiments, plus a repeatable way to turn each PDF into
markdown an agent can read. This file is the workflow; it's written for the agent
that maintains the library.

Only three things are versioned: `ressources.json` (the catalog),
`convert_pdf.py` (the conversion script), and this `README.md`. Every per-paper
folder is derived from them and is rebuilt on demand, so it stays out of git.

## Structure

```
ressources/
    .gitignore           # ignores every <slug>/ folder
    README.md            # this file
    convert_pdf.py       # slug-driven docling conversion
    ressources.json      # the catalog
    <slug>/              # rebuildable, git-ignored
        _input.pdf       # the paper, from the entry's url (or supplied by hand)
        _output.md       # docling markdown export
        images/          # figures docling extracted, referenced by _output.md
        summary.md       # your summary of _output.md + images/
```

## The catalog

`ressources.json` is an array of entries. Each has:

- `slug` — unique kebab-case key, and the folder name under `ressources/`.
- `title` — the paper's title.
- `url` — direct link to the PDF (e.g. `https://arxiv.org/pdf/2002.05709`).
- `date` — publication date, ISO `YYYY-MM-DD`.
- `repo` — code repository, or `null` when there's none.

## Add a resource

1. Add an entry to `ressources.json` with a fresh `slug`.
2. Run the converter:

   ```bash
   uv run ressources/convert_pdf.py <slug>
   ```

   If the host blocks automatic downloads, download the PDF by hand and pass it
   in — it becomes `_input.pdf` and the rest is identical:

   ```bash
   uv run ressources/convert_pdf.py <slug> --pdf ~/Downloads/paper.pdf
   ```

   This writes `_input.pdf`, `_output.md`, and `images/`. Add `--force` to
   re-download and re-convert an entry that already has outputs.
3. Read `_output.md` and the figures in `images/`, then write `summary.md`.

## What a summary contains

Write `summary.md` for a future agent deciding whether the paper is worth
opening in full. Cover:

- the problem and why it matters,
- the method — the core idea, loss, and architecture in enough detail to place it,
- the key results and what they show,
- notable figures, referencing them by their path in `images/`,
- links to the paper (`url`) and its `repo`.

Keep it concrete and follow `../.guidelines-ai/avoid-ai-slop.md`.

## Rebuild from scratch

The whole point of keeping only the three tracked files: an agent can rebuild
every folder from them. "Read this README and process every resource in
`ressources.json`" means

```bash
uv run ressources/convert_pdf.py --all
```

to regenerate every `_input.pdf`, `_output.md`, and `images/`, then write each
`summary.md`. Papers with `--pdf`-only sources (blocked downloads) are the one
exception — they need the file supplied by hand.

## Commands

```bash
uv run ressources/convert_pdf.py <slug>              # one paper
uv run ressources/convert_pdf.py <slug> --pdf <path> # blocked download
uv run ressources/convert_pdf.py --all               # every paper
uv run ressources/convert_pdf.py <slug> --force      # redo an existing one
```
